threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, missing section headers at jd

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: VoidLink Implant Core v3.0, a highly sophisticated Linux RAT/Backdoor. The sample exhibits advanced malware behaviors including: 1. Extensive environment enumeration for virtualization (VMware, KVM), containers (Docker, Kubernetes), and cloud providers (AWS, GCP, Azure, Alibaba, Tencent); 2. Credential harvesting of SSH known_hosts, config files, shell histories (.bash_history, .zsh_history), and cloud metadata; 3. Rootkit functionality utilizing both traditional Linux Kernel Modules (LKM) and eBPF programs to hide network connections and files (references to kprobes and stealth_netstat); 4. Dynamic compilation of malicious kernel modules on the victim host using local build tools; 5. Command-and-Control (C2) communication via HTTP with modular plugin support and Base64-encoded payloads. Relevant IOCs include the use of '/tmp/.vl_tmp.ko', '/tmp/.vl_cmd.sh', '/tmp/.vl_hide_cfg' for internal files and C2 endpoints like '/api/v2/sync' and '/api/poll'.
